---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import srcImage from "../../assets/best-trout-fishing-spots-beaverton-oregon.png";
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import MyH1 from "../../components/MyH1.astro";
import Bests from "../../components/Bests.astro";
---
<Layout 
title="Best trout fishing spots near Beverton, Oregon"
description="Comprehensive guide to best trout fishing hotspots – with seasonal tips, gear suggestions, and local insights."
url="https://beverton.oregonfishingforum.com/trout/best-spots/"
type="article"
site_name="Oregon Fishing Forum"
ogimage={srcImage.src}
>
    <div class="text-center">
        <MyH1 text="Best trout fishing spots near Beverton, Oregon" />
        <p class="mb-4">Comprehensive guide to best trout fishing hotspots – with seasonal tips, gear suggestions, and local insights.</p>

        <Image
            src={srcImage}
            alt="Best trout fishing spots near Beverton, Oregon"
            loading={"eager"}
            fetchpriority={"high"}
            class="rounded-xl shadow mx-auto"
            />
            <br>
    </div>

<h3>
    <strong>1. Commonwealth Lake (Cedar Hills area)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        A stocked suburban pond ideal for family outings, with ADA-accessible docks and paved trails 
    </li>
    <li>
        Regularly stocked from March–May with rainbow trout—great for PowerBait, worms, or small spinners
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>2. Bethany Lake (Northwest Beaverton)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Pristine pond with seasonal rainbow stocking and occasional bass/crappie 
    </li>
    <li>
        Easily accessible with paved trails and good for beginner or family fishing.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>3. Progress Lake (Progress Ridge)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Former quarry pond with deep, cool water—perfect for trout after stocking 
    </li>
    <li>
        Ideal for line-and-bobber setups; worth visiting right after fish are stocked.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>4. Henry Hagg Lake (near Gaston)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        A large reservoir ~25 min away, stocked with “trophy-size” trout every spring and fall 
    </li>
    <li>
        Offers excellent bank and boat access with ADA-friendly piers at Boat Ramp C
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>5. Tualatin River &amp; Tributaries</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Cool stretches hold wild trout in headwater areas like Dairy, McKay, and Gales Creeks 
    </li>
    <li>
        Boat and bank access via Rood Bridge Park, Cook Park, and Gales Creek campground&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>6. Upper Clackamas River &amp; Oak Grove Fork</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Roughly an hour away, this offers wild rainbows, cutthroats, brook, and brown trout 
    </li>
    <li>
        Closed to bait—fly and artificial only—which helps preserve water quality.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>7. Trout Creek (Mt. Hood foothills)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        A smaller stream that’s great for fly anglers seeking cutthroat trout 
    </li>
    <li>
        Peaceful and scenic—worth the drive for a quiet wade-fishing experience.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    When to Go &amp; Top Techniques
</h2>
<figure class="table">
    <table>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>
                    <strong>Season</strong>
                </th>
                <th>
                    <strong>Best Spots</strong>
                </th>
                <th>
                    <strong>Recommended Setup</strong>
                </th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td>
                    Spring (Mar–May)
                </td>
                <td>
                    Commonwealth, Bethany, Progress after stocking
                </td>
                <td>
                    PowerBait, worms under bobber, small spinners
                </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>
                    Summer (Jun–Aug)
                </td>
                <td>
                    Hagg Lake (early/late), Tualatin tributaries
                </td>
                <td>
                    Spoons, spinners, topwater lures
                </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>
                    Fall (Sep–Oct)
                </td>
                <td>
                    Hagg Lake, Oak Grove Fork, Trout Creek
                </td>
                <td>
                    Dry flies, nymphs, shallow trolling
                </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>
                    Winter (Dec–Feb)
                </td>
                <td>
                    Commonwealth (warmer days), Tualatin Creek
                </td>
                <td>
                    PowerBait, worms, small spoons in shallows
                </td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>
</figure>
<p>
    &nbsp;
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        Fish just after stocking for best results 
    </li>
    <li>
        Early morning and late evening are top bite windows&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Pro Tips for Beaverton Trout Fishing
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Check the ODFW stocking schedule</strong>—they’re reliable for timing your trip 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Keep gear simple:</strong> PowerBait rigs, worms, or small spinners are ideal for urban ponds.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Bring a boat or kayak</strong> for reservoirs like Hagg Lake to reach deeper, fish-holding areas 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Respect rules:</strong> Many streams restrict bait and enforce catch limits—check ODFW regulations before heading out .
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    Summary: Best Spots at a Glance
</h3>
<ol>
    <li>
        <strong>Commonwealth Lake</strong> – Easy, accessible, great for kids/families
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Bethany Lake</strong> – Central, stocked trout, beginner-friendly
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Progress Lake</strong> – Deep suburban pond with summer trout
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Henry Hagg Lake</strong> – Trophy trout reservoir; bank/boat access
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Tualatin tributaries</strong> – Wild trout in scenic creek settings
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Upper Clackamas &amp; Oak Grove Fork</strong> – Fly-fishing hotspot
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Trout Creek</strong> – Remote creek with cutthroats &amp; wild trout
    </li>
</ol>

<Bests />
</Layout>